{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"58fe74af-dce5-4212-8e59-b1bf852dc362","content":"Here's the correct attribute for each framework:\n\n| Framework | Attribute |\n|-----------|-----------|\n| **MSTest** | `[Ignore(\"reason\")]` |\n| **xUnit** | `[Fact(Skip = \"reason\")]` or `[Theory(Skip = \"reason\")]` |\n| **NUnit** | `[Ignore(\"reason\")]` |\n| **TUnit** | `[Skip(\"reason\")]` |\n\n**Example usage:**\n\n```csharp\n// MSTest\n[TestMethod]\n[Ignore(\"Blocked by bug #123\")]\npublic void MyMsTest() { }\n\n// xUnit\n[Fact(Skip = \"Blocked by bug #123\")]\npublic void MyXunitTest() { }\n\n// NUnit\n[Test]\n[Ignore(\"Blocked by bug #123\")]\npublic void MyNunitTest() { }\n\n// TUnit\n[Test]\n[Skip(\"Blocked by bug #123\")]\npublic void MyTunitTest() { }\n```\n\nKey differences: xUnit embeds the skip reason directly in `[Fact]`/`[Theory]` rather than using a separate attribute. The other three use standalone attributes alongside their test markers.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"90cce47d-bfb0-48b8-9fa3-88dcfdfee0e3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about test-skipping attributes across four .NET test frameworks. This is a knowledge question - no tools needed.","outputTokens":319,"requestId":"A02A:197E70:18053E4:1B50B69:69FE8A23"},"id":"07180d42-49c3-4828-adb7-ee1205948a67","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:13:13.933Z","parentId":"74418434-2ba7-4d57-9395-f9514cc7444a"}
